Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.790 --> 00:00:03.970
&gt;&gt; From the Library of
Congress in Washington, D.C.

00:00:07.100 --> 00:00:09.270
&gt;&gt; E.A. Aymar: Thank you so much
to everyone for coming out to Noir

00:00:09.270 --> 00:00:11.760
at the National Book Festival
and thanks to the Library

00:00:11.760 --> 00:00:13.470
of Congress for having us.

00:00:13.470 --> 00:00:17.180
And we owe a special debt to
Colleen Slogan and Nicolas Brown

00:00:17.180 --> 00:00:19.110
for arranging this event
and putting Noir at the Bar

00:00:19.110 --> 00:00:21.410
in the national spotlight.

00:00:24.040 --> 00:00:26.820
For those of you who've never
been to a Noir at the Bar,

00:00:26.820 --> 00:00:29.180
it's an event that was
started about a decade ago

00:00:29.180 --> 00:00:33.250
by the crime fiction book blogger
Pete Rozosky in Philadelphia.

00:00:33.250 --> 00:00:36.990
Basically, a group of crime fiction
writers get together in a bar,

00:00:36.990 --> 00:00:40.790
drink, and read short
stories or excerpts of novels.

00:00:40.790 --> 00:00:42.710
Given the bar setting, the alcohol,

00:00:42.710 --> 00:00:45.760
and the fact that crime fiction
writers tend to enjoy hanging

00:00:45.760 --> 00:00:49.040
out in the outskirts of
respected literary society,

00:00:49.040 --> 00:00:52.300
these readings are usually
raunchy and full of vulgarity,

00:00:52.300 --> 00:00:56.880
but generally stayed true to
Noir or Neo-Noir tradition.

00:00:56.880 --> 00:00:58.180
See, you learned something.

00:00:58.180 --> 00:00:59.480
That's it, though.

00:00:59.480 --> 00:01:00.980
That's all you'll learn tonight.

00:01:00.980 --> 00:01:03.340
Given that this is a
family event and we'd

00:01:03.340 --> 00:01:06.220
like to come back next year, we're
going to cut down on the raunch

00:01:06.220 --> 00:01:09.840
and the swearing, but we'll still
have a fair amount of sketchiness

00:01:09.840 --> 00:01:13.230
and shady characters,
which leads us right

00:01:13.230 --> 00:01:16.230
to our first reader,
Louis Bayard [laughing].

00:01:16.230 --> 00:01:19.730
There he is.

00:01:19.730 --> 00:01:23.710 position:56%
Louis eight novels include the Edgar
nominated, "The Pale Blue Eye,"

00:01:23.710 --> 00:01:26.750
the New York Times notable,
"Mr. Timothy," and the recent

00:01:26.750 --> 00:01:31.140
"Lucky Strikes" named one of the
best young adult titles of 2016.

00:01:31.140 --> 00:01:33.970 position:56%
His other novels include, "The
Black Tower," "The School of Night,"

00:01:33.970 --> 00:01:35.480
and, "Roosevelt's Beast."

00:01:35.480 --> 00:01:38.000
His essays and articles have
appeared in the Los Angeles

00:01:38.000 --> 00:01:41.770
and New York Times, the Washington
Post, Salon, and book form.

00:01:41.770 --> 00:01:44.900
He was also the author of
the Downton Abbey Recaps

00:01:44.900 --> 00:01:49.260
for The New York Times, which
he embarrassingly called

00:01:49.260 --> 00:01:52.380
"Downtown Abbey" well
into the second season.

00:01:52.380 --> 00:01:54.180
Here's Louis.

00:01:54.180 --> 00:02:05.280
[ Applause ]

00:02:05.280 --> 00:02:07.290
&gt;&gt; Louis Bayard: I knew Ed
would spread lies about me.

00:02:07.290 --> 00:02:08.590
I knew it.

00:02:08.590 --> 00:02:11.330
It's just one of those things
that you knew was going to happen.

00:02:11.330 --> 00:02:12.630
Well, welcome, everybody.

00:02:12.630 --> 00:02:13.930
It's great to be here.

00:02:13.930 --> 00:02:17.690 position:56%
And thank you, Ed, for organizing us
all and getting us here [applause].

00:02:17.690 --> 00:02:22.300
Yeah. I think it's hilarious we're
in the children's space right now

00:02:22.300 --> 00:02:24.510 position:56%
and I've been -- I'm already busily,

00:02:24.510 --> 00:02:27.380
fiercely editing what
I have to read tonight.

00:02:27.380 --> 00:02:28.730
Just a brief introduction.

00:02:28.730 --> 00:02:30.760
A few years back, a
friend and I were leafing

00:02:30.760 --> 00:02:33.990
through the DC Noir anthology

00:02:33.990 --> 00:02:36.660
in would Jim Grady was
permanently featured.

00:02:36.660 --> 00:02:38.190
I -- at least Jim Grady.

00:02:38.190 --> 00:02:39.490
Maybe [inaudible].

00:02:39.490 --> 00:02:42.110
And we realized suddenly that
there were no gay writers in it.

00:02:42.110 --> 00:02:45.830
At least no writers that we'd
ever dated before between us.

00:02:45.830 --> 00:02:51.190
And that led to this whole
conversation about Gay Noir

00:02:51.190 --> 00:02:53.660
and whether such a
thing was even possible.

00:02:53.660 --> 00:02:57.750 position:56%
I, of course, contended that it was,
and to prove it, I wrote this story,

00:02:57.750 --> 00:02:59.050
which was eventually published

00:02:59.050 --> 00:03:02.190
in the City Paper's
annual fiction issue.

00:03:02.190 --> 00:03:06.320
And, in fact, the story is
set in DC in the late '80s

00:03:06.320 --> 00:03:08.530
and it's titled, "Chesapeake."

00:03:08.530 --> 00:03:12.440
Not after the bay, I
should add, but the bar.

00:03:12.440 --> 00:03:18.340
The Chesapeake house, which was
a really sleazy gay strip club

00:03:18.340 --> 00:03:21.780
that used to draw a crowd
back in the day not very far

00:03:21.780 --> 00:03:23.440
from here, in fact, very close by.

00:03:23.440 --> 00:03:25.450
So this is how this story begins.

00:03:25.450 --> 00:03:29.570 position:56%
And this will be -- this will be PG.

00:03:29.570 --> 00:03:34.290
A quarter century ago, or
maybe it was a million years,

00:03:34.290 --> 00:03:38.500
I dated a full lipped, morally
unanchored charmer named Benjamin

00:03:38.500 --> 00:03:41.240
who was in his third
year of Georgetown Law.

00:03:41.240 --> 00:03:43.990
Better to say I tried to date him.

00:03:43.990 --> 00:03:47.060
One night, because he
wouldn't cut me loose

00:03:47.060 --> 00:03:50.580
and because I couldn't cut myself
loose, and because abjection came

00:03:50.580 --> 00:03:54.130
as naturally to me then as
breathing, I followed him

00:03:54.130 --> 00:03:58.140
without his knowledge from
Badlands down P Street.

00:03:58.140 --> 00:04:00.590
He crossed DuPont Circle,
cut up New Hampshire, then,

00:04:00.590 --> 00:04:03.810
a little shy of U Street
he paused in front

00:04:03.810 --> 00:04:06.540
of a cinnamon brick
apartment building.

00:04:06.540 --> 00:04:09.060
Like a mariner back
from the Spice Islands,

00:04:09.060 --> 00:04:12.150 position:56%
he gazed up at a second floor window

00:04:12.150 --> 00:04:15.850
where a lamp was even now
extending a tongue of light.

00:04:15.850 --> 00:04:18.260
He nodded to himself and then
made straight for the vestibule

00:04:18.260 --> 00:04:20.830
where he waited for
the answering buzz.

00:04:20.830 --> 00:04:23.250
In less than a minute his shadow,

00:04:23.250 --> 00:04:26.400
unmistakable with his
lacrosse shoulders,

00:04:26.400 --> 00:04:28.800
flickered across the
apartment's curtains.

00:04:28.800 --> 00:04:30.520
This much I knew.

00:04:30.520 --> 00:04:32.900
He would eat before
he did anything else.

00:04:32.900 --> 00:04:37.240
Twenty minutes later an order
from Trio Pizza arrived.

00:04:37.240 --> 00:04:40.140 position:56%
I slipped in after the delivery guy,
followed him to the second floor,

00:04:40.140 --> 00:04:45.750
watched a door spring open, saw
a pair of hands, not Benjamin's.

00:04:45.750 --> 00:04:48.640
Apartment 203.

00:04:48.640 --> 00:04:52.920
The blaze of revelation subsided as
I planted myself opposite the door.

00:04:52.920 --> 00:04:57.190
If I were to have the confrontation
I wanted, needed, feared,

00:04:57.190 --> 00:04:59.120
I'd have to sit there for
the rest of the evening,

00:04:59.120 --> 00:05:01.540
my back against the wall.

00:05:01.540 --> 00:05:06.480
Instead, I fell asleep and woke an
uncertain number of hours later.

00:05:06.480 --> 00:05:11.300
A slender young man was standing in
the open doorway of apartment 203

00:05:11.300 --> 00:05:14.700
in a pair of oversized sweatpants.

00:05:14.700 --> 00:05:16.000
I lurched to my feet.

00:05:16.000 --> 00:05:18.820
"Sorry, I'm Knox.

00:05:18.820 --> 00:05:20.530
Like the fort.

00:05:20.530 --> 00:05:24.170
Yeah." "Benjamin's gone, sweetie."

00:05:24.170 --> 00:05:27.840
The voice was soft and low,
but with Carolina vowels.

00:05:27.840 --> 00:05:29.370
"I doubt he even saw you there.

00:05:29.370 --> 00:05:32.730
He was in a hurry to get to class."

00:05:32.730 --> 00:05:35.770
Even in my sleep dazzled state
I could discern two things.

00:05:35.770 --> 00:05:41.070
The young man was lying and this
lying was a form of charity.

00:05:41.070 --> 00:05:42.740
"I'm Joey," he said.

00:05:42.740 --> 00:05:44.700
"You should come in."

00:05:44.700 --> 00:05:48.520
He made a pot of Irish breakfast
and poured it out in beer mugs.

00:05:48.520 --> 00:05:50.700
He fed me Danish and Jiffy Pop.

00:05:50.700 --> 00:05:52.490
He loaned me a comb.

00:05:52.490 --> 00:05:56.920
The clock radio on his kitchen
counter had ticked just past 11AM

00:05:56.920 --> 00:05:59.590
when he leaned across his
biscuit crate coffee table

00:05:59.590 --> 00:06:04.780
and folded his soft, white fingers
around my long, thin, veined ones.

00:06:04.780 --> 00:06:09.080
"You know, he's not
worth this," he said.

00:06:09.080 --> 00:06:12.980
It occurred to me to deny it, but,
in the next breath, Joey said,

00:06:12.980 --> 00:06:16.220
"I think I'm done with him too."

00:06:16.220 --> 00:06:20.710
Decades later I'm still unpacking
the grace of that moment,

00:06:20.710 --> 00:06:24.860
one man able, in just a
few words, to free two men,

00:06:24.860 --> 00:06:26.830
to take them both out of the hunt.

00:06:26.830 --> 00:06:28.980
"Do you have a place
to stay tonight?"

00:06:28.980 --> 00:06:32.260
he asked. The answer was, "No."

00:06:32.260 --> 00:06:34.620
I had just been evicted from
your apartment in Mount Pleasant.

00:06:34.620 --> 00:06:38.600
My belongings were somewhere
in the attic over city lights

00:06:38.600 --> 00:06:41.480
and I was waiting to hear
about a studio in Shaw.

00:06:41.480 --> 00:06:45.020
I was 23. I'd come to
Washington not for a career,

00:06:45.020 --> 00:06:48.970
but for a boy and I was dying.

00:06:48.970 --> 00:06:51.530
But we all were.

00:06:51.530 --> 00:06:55.110
"The couch pulls out," said Joey.

00:06:55.110 --> 00:06:57.300
I lay on that couch
for about a week.

00:06:57.300 --> 00:06:58.600
Joey cleaned around me.

00:06:58.600 --> 00:07:00.390
He was a terror about dust.

00:07:00.390 --> 00:07:03.780
And when he got tired of that, he
draped the Thursday classifieds

00:07:03.780 --> 00:07:06.990
over me, "just in case," he said.

00:07:06.990 --> 00:07:08.920
I wasn't very employable then.

00:07:08.920 --> 00:07:12.240
Two years of a crunchy liberal arts
college in central Pennsylvania,

00:07:12.240 --> 00:07:15.830
segments of office slavery,
a moderate acquaintanceship

00:07:15.830 --> 00:07:18.530
with Word Star and MultiMate.

00:07:18.530 --> 00:07:21.550
The old people here
will know those things.

00:07:21.550 --> 00:07:23.850
But I beefed up my
resume as much as I dared

00:07:23.850 --> 00:07:25.720
and flooded every office in town.

00:07:25.720 --> 00:07:27.320
No one called back.

00:07:27.320 --> 00:07:31.080
For cash I took gigs bussing
tables at the American Cafe,

00:07:31.080 --> 00:07:34.760
answering phones at an
optometric association modeling

00:07:34.760 --> 00:07:38.570
in the deep background
of a Sheraton print ad.

00:07:38.570 --> 00:07:41.550
Sometimes, in a brief
flush of solvency,

00:07:41.550 --> 00:07:43.650
I would offer to write
Joey a check for the rent,

00:07:43.650 --> 00:07:45.120
but he waved his hand at me.

00:07:45.120 --> 00:07:47.450
"When the ship comes in."

00:07:47.450 --> 00:07:50.770
Never once did I see him write a
check of his own nor could I begin

00:07:50.770 --> 00:07:55.230 position:56%
to say whose name was on the lease
or who was paying for our groceries.

00:07:55.230 --> 00:07:58.390
The bowls of citrus fruit on the
kitchen counter, the whole chickens

00:07:58.390 --> 00:08:01.860
in the freezer, the packages
of Tuna Helper in the cupboard,

00:08:01.860 --> 00:08:04.530
they were just there waiting.

00:08:04.530 --> 00:08:07.830
Most days Joey slept until one or
two in the afternoon and it wasn't

00:08:07.830 --> 00:08:09.640
until eight or nine in the
evening that he would put

00:08:09.640 --> 00:08:15.050 position:56%
on his denim shorts and his two polo
shirts and go off to see his friend.

00:08:15.050 --> 00:08:19.400
Friend being, in this case, a
category rather than an individual.

00:08:19.400 --> 00:08:22.640
The one job I knew him to
hold down was as a dancer

00:08:22.640 --> 00:08:25.270
at the Chesapeake House
and only because he invited

00:08:25.270 --> 00:08:27.720
on impulse to watch him perform.

00:08:27.720 --> 00:08:29.970
Of the three guys dancing
on the runway that night,

00:08:29.970 --> 00:08:33.770
he was the oldest, which
is to say he was 23,

00:08:33.770 --> 00:08:35.840
but the most boyish in appearance.

00:08:35.840 --> 00:08:41.660
He wore a jock strap, gray
athletic socks, and white Tretorns,

00:08:41.660 --> 00:08:44.150
and he moved in a benign fog,

00:08:44.150 --> 00:08:46.280
as though we were all
part of his dream.

00:08:46.280 --> 00:08:47.700
I hustled him out of the place --

00:08:47.700 --> 00:08:49.650
I hustled out of the
place before midnight.

00:08:49.650 --> 00:08:53.990
Joey told me later I'd
missed the Scottish fantasia.

00:08:53.990 --> 00:08:55.290
That's oblique enough.

00:08:55.290 --> 00:08:56.820
Right? That's oblique enough.

00:08:56.820 --> 00:08:59.040
[ Laughter ]

00:08:59.040 --> 00:09:00.700
Our schedules were ideally matched.

00:09:00.700 --> 00:09:03.510
If I wanted to bring
a trick home from --

00:09:03.510 --> 00:09:07.430
[ Laughter ]

00:09:07.430 --> 00:09:08.730
&gt;&gt; Keep going!

00:09:08.730 --> 00:09:10.090
&gt;&gt; Louis Bayard: If I wanted
to bring a gentleman home

00:09:10.090 --> 00:09:15.850
from Tracks [laughter] or the Frat
House, Joey would already be gone,

00:09:15.850 --> 00:09:19.140
and by the time the gentleman
was living the next morning,

00:09:19.140 --> 00:09:22.600
Joey was just coming back,
laden with rolls and oranges.

00:09:22.600 --> 00:09:23.900
"Have a blessed day!"

00:09:23.900 --> 00:09:25.200
he'd call out.

00:09:25.200 --> 00:09:27.860
Our only moment of intersection
came late in the afternoon when,

00:09:27.860 --> 00:09:30.950 position:56%
like an old married couple, we would
sit on the chapped leather couch

00:09:30.950 --> 00:09:32.830
and watch the squawk box.

00:09:32.830 --> 00:09:36.040 position:56%
Neither Joey nor I had any sure idea
of what was going on in the world,

00:09:36.040 --> 00:09:39.830 position:56%
but we both found the news
mysteriously restful, like listening

00:09:39.830 --> 00:09:43.840
to traffic reports for
highways you would never travel.

00:09:43.840 --> 00:09:46.630
So it was that, one afternoon
in June, our eyes came to rest

00:09:46.630 --> 00:09:48.880
on a perfectly unremarkable
press conference,

00:09:48.880 --> 00:09:52.150
three legislators before
a thicket of microphones.

00:09:52.150 --> 00:09:57.040
The third man was halfway through
his remarks when Joey said, "Oh.

00:09:57.040 --> 00:09:59.520
That's Earflaps."

00:09:59.520 --> 00:10:03.340 position:56%
Well, Earflaps, in addition to being
a Kansas republican is a sometime

00:10:03.340 --> 00:10:06.190
patron of the Chesapeake House.

00:10:06.190 --> 00:10:08.430
So, from here the tale
becomes increasingly twisted.

00:10:08.430 --> 00:10:13.700 position:56%
It includes blackmail, an unexpected
death, and rueful life lessons.

00:10:13.700 --> 00:10:18.450
And you can Google the rest of it
on the internet at your leisure,

00:10:18.450 --> 00:10:19.750
or maybe, cross your fingers,

00:10:19.750 --> 00:10:23.440
look for it in the
next DC Noir anthology.

00:10:23.440 --> 00:10:25.510
Thank you very much.

00:10:25.510 --> 00:10:39.980
[ Applause ]

00:10:39.980 --> 00:10:41.480
