00:13:20.010 --> 00:13:22.570
So we gave her a bonus and
promised to recommend her to others

00:13:22.570 --> 00:13:25.740
and then we forgot about her.

00:13:25.740 --> 00:13:29.320
Months later, I came home and found
the cat's dishes in the middle

00:13:29.320 --> 00:13:31.290
of the living room floor.

00:13:31.290 --> 00:13:33.490
I looked to George
Harrison for explanation,

00:13:33.490 --> 00:13:37.000
but he merely licked a paw
and stalked out of the room.

00:13:37.000 --> 00:13:40.960
I shrugged and returned the dishes
to the kitchen where they belonged.

00:13:40.960 --> 00:13:44.530
The next day I came home to
find the dishes moved again.

00:13:44.530 --> 00:13:47.770
When I questioned James, he
looked at me like I was crazy.

00:13:47.770 --> 00:13:49.830
"I haven't been doing that."

00:13:49.830 --> 00:13:51.130
"Do we have a poltergeist?"

00:13:51.130 --> 00:13:52.710
I wondered.

00:13:52.710 --> 00:13:54.290
"Maybe you're just not
getting enough sleep, Hun."

00:13:54.290 --> 00:13:57.800
I might have accepted
his explanation

00:13:57.800 --> 00:13:59.990
if things hadn't started happening.

00:13:59.990 --> 00:14:02.350
I found the silverware
piled on the table,

00:14:02.350 --> 00:14:05.300
the books rearranged
spines facing in,

00:14:05.300 --> 00:14:09.530
a wine glass we hadn't used
drying on a kitchen towel.

00:14:09.530 --> 00:14:12.230
James accused me of doing
all this to screw with him

00:14:12.230 --> 00:14:14.310 position:56%
and I wondered if I was cracking up.

00:14:14.310 --> 00:14:16.590
But then some money went missing.

00:14:16.590 --> 00:14:19.450
Not much, but enough
that we noticed.

00:14:19.450 --> 00:14:22.560
And I realized somebody
must be coming to the house.

00:14:22.560 --> 00:14:25.220
But who? There are no
signs of a break-in

00:14:25.220 --> 00:14:28.870
and James' mother was the
only one with a set of keys.

00:14:28.870 --> 00:14:33.010
I doubted she was leaving her
retirement community to prank us.

00:14:33.010 --> 00:14:35.210
And then we remembered Megan.

00:14:35.210 --> 00:14:36.870
It was so obvious.

00:14:36.870 --> 00:14:39.990
She must have made a
copy of our house keys.

00:14:39.990 --> 00:14:42.150
"We know what you're
doing," James told her

00:14:42.150 --> 00:14:44.430
over the phone, "and
you need to stop."

00:14:44.430 --> 00:14:46.620
"I don't know what
you're talking about,"

00:14:46.620 --> 00:14:49.390
she said coolly and hung up on us.

00:14:49.390 --> 00:14:53.680
But the call put a stop to
things, or we thought it did.

00:14:53.680 --> 00:14:56.500
One week later, James
called me into the study.

00:14:56.500 --> 00:14:59.660
He gestured to an open desk
drawer and asked, his voice tight,

00:14:59.660 --> 00:15:02.630
"Have you moved anything?"

00:15:02.630 --> 00:15:04.040
I knew that drawer.

00:15:04.040 --> 00:15:05.910
I knew what he was asking me.

00:15:05.910 --> 00:15:09.360 position:56%
That was the drawer where James
kept the pot he sold and I could see

00:15:09.360 --> 00:15:10.660
from where I was standing

00:15:10.660 --> 00:15:13.390
that it was strangely
empty except for a scale.

00:15:13.390 --> 00:15:16.270
It wasn't like James was
some sort of drug dealer.

00:15:16.270 --> 00:15:20.100
He was a hobbyist just procuring
some stuff from his younger cousin,

00:15:20.100 --> 00:15:23.700
this skinny skateboard punk
who actually was a drug dealer,

00:15:23.700 --> 00:15:26.580
and then, you know, distributing
it to some friends all

00:15:26.580 --> 00:15:30.620
of whom were happy to reimburse
James for his cost and maybe also

00:15:30.620 --> 00:15:32.910
to throw in a little extra
for his time and effort.

00:15:32.910 --> 00:15:34.410
Hardly Walter White.

00:15:34.410 --> 00:15:35.710
But still.

00:15:35.710 --> 00:15:37.390
I kept my hands as far
away from that as possible

00:15:37.390 --> 00:15:40.630
and I sure hadn't moved anything.

00:15:40.630 --> 00:15:41.930
"Megan." I said.

00:15:41.930 --> 00:15:43.620
"Who else could it have been?"

00:15:43.620 --> 00:15:46.070
Because, of course, there
was no other answer.

00:15:46.070 --> 00:15:48.270
We had told Megan where we
kept the keys to that desk,

00:15:48.270 --> 00:15:51.330
had basically handed
her unfettered access

00:15:51.330 --> 00:15:52.970
to our records and our secrets.

00:15:52.970 --> 00:15:55.060
How had we have been so stupid
to think she would be put off

00:15:55.060 --> 00:15:56.760
by one half-baked phone call?

00:15:56.760 --> 00:16:00.040
"Do you think she's been taking
small amounts for weeks now?"

00:16:00.040 --> 00:16:02.970
I asked, "Distracting us
from her theft with things

00:16:02.970 --> 00:16:04.270
like moving the cat's dishes?

00:16:04.270 --> 00:16:08.740 position:56%
And do you think she took everything
in retribution for that call?"

00:16:08.740 --> 00:16:12.950
"I don't know," James growled,
"but we have to get it back.

00:16:12.950 --> 00:16:14.250
I'm going over there."

00:16:14.250 --> 00:16:18.070
I ran to put on shoes
and met James by the car.

00:16:18.070 --> 00:16:20.850
There was a cold, unfamiliar
look in his eyes,

00:16:20.850 --> 00:16:24.090
something that made him look a bit
dangerous, which was ridiculous

00:16:24.090 --> 00:16:25.710
because James couldn't
even hurt a spider.

00:16:25.710 --> 00:16:27.880
He was always trapping
those things under glasses

00:16:27.880 --> 00:16:29.950
and releasing them outside.

00:16:29.950 --> 00:16:32.140
Still, I had a feeling
I needed to go with him

00:16:32.140 --> 00:16:34.960
to make sure things
didn't get out of hand.

00:16:34.960 --> 00:16:39.100 position:56%
Megan seemed bewildered to find us
on her doorstep, which was ludicrous

00:16:39.100 --> 00:16:41.230
because she had been breaking
into our home for weeks

00:16:41.230 --> 00:16:44.180
and had just stolen
a bunch of drugs.

00:16:44.180 --> 00:16:46.430
She held the door open less
than a foot and asked us

00:16:46.430 --> 00:16:49.830
with faux concern whether
George Harrison was all right.

00:16:49.830 --> 00:16:54.610
I snarled at her, "There's no
need to bring the cat into this."

00:16:54.610 --> 00:16:56.750
James isn't a big man, but
he was bigger than Megan

00:16:56.750 --> 00:17:00.480
and he pushed the door wide
open and barreled inside.

00:17:00.480 --> 00:17:02.570
I followed him closing
the door behind us

00:17:02.570 --> 00:17:04.880 position:56%
as Megan's eyes got wide with worry.

00:17:04.880 --> 00:17:07.850
I started to tell her that she
should stop looking so surprised.

00:17:07.850 --> 00:17:09.410
She was the one who
had started all this,

00:17:09.410 --> 00:17:13.320 position:56%
when I noticed a paperweight
pinning down some mail by a table --

00:17:13.320 --> 00:17:15.350
on a table by the front door.

00:17:15.350 --> 00:17:18.200
And not just any paperweight.

00:17:18.200 --> 00:17:20.120
It was our paperweight.

00:17:20.120 --> 00:17:24.050
A glass globe that my late mother
had given us as a wedding gift.

00:17:24.050 --> 00:17:27.370 position:56%
We kept it in the study atop the
desk whose drawers Megan had raided.

00:17:27.370 --> 00:17:30.000
I snatched it up and
waved it at her.

00:17:30.000 --> 00:17:32.050
"You stole this too?"

00:17:32.050 --> 00:17:34.910
She narrowed her eyes,
shook her head,

00:17:34.910 --> 00:17:37.610
claimed she had no idea
what I was talking about.

00:17:37.610 --> 00:17:39.250
"Just give us back our stuff."

00:17:39.250 --> 00:17:41.340
James said reasonably.

00:17:41.340 --> 00:17:42.960
She insisted she didn't
know what we meant,

00:17:42.960 --> 00:17:45.750
that she didn't have
any of our stuff.

00:17:45.750 --> 00:17:47.050
"Then what's this?"

00:17:47.050 --> 00:17:50.260
I demanded waving the
paperweight at her.

00:17:50.260 --> 00:17:54.120 position:56%
She ignored me looking over my
shoulder with wide, frightened eyes,

00:17:54.120 --> 00:17:56.390
her mouth dropped open slightly.

00:17:56.390 --> 00:17:59.330
"That's not how she usually looks
at James," I thought absurdly.

00:17:59.330 --> 00:18:03.610
I turned to follow her gaze and
saw James was holding a gun at her.

00:18:03.610 --> 00:18:07.200
"Wow!" I said, "Where
did that come from?"

00:18:07.200 --> 00:18:10.680
"That's it," Megan
said, all false bravado

00:18:10.680 --> 00:18:12.070
as she pulled her phone
from her pocket.

00:18:12.070 --> 00:18:13.370
"I'm calling the cops."

00:18:13.370 --> 00:18:17.950
But I couldn't let her do
that, especially not now,

00:18:17.950 --> 00:18:19.880
not with James waving
around some gun

00:18:19.880 --> 00:18:22.020
that he got from who knows where.

00:18:22.020 --> 00:18:25.820
I knew that, but I didn't
know what I could do about it.

00:18:25.820 --> 00:18:28.180
I didn't know that I had
done anything about it

00:18:28.180 --> 00:18:31.220
until I heard James'
shocked inhalation and looked

00:18:31.220 --> 00:18:33.930
down to find Megan
crumpled on the carpet.

00:18:33.930 --> 00:18:35.730
James looked at me horrified.

00:18:35.730 --> 00:18:37.620
"What did you just do?"

00:18:37.620 --> 00:18:40.590
I looked down at the
paperweight in my hand.

00:18:40.590 --> 00:18:43.420
Blood dripped off the green
glass sphere staining the carpet.

00:18:43.420 --> 00:18:44.740
I frowned.

00:18:44.740 --> 00:18:47.350
I had always thought this
paperweight was blue.

00:18:47.350 --> 00:18:50.070
But I couldn't worry
about shades of blue

00:18:50.070 --> 00:18:53.910
and green while there was a
woman lying dead on the carpet.

00:18:53.910 --> 00:18:55.210
We left her there.

00:18:55.210 --> 00:18:57.080
We didn't know what else to do.

00:18:57.080 --> 00:19:00.470
We thought back to every Law and
Order episode we had ever watched

00:19:00.470 --> 00:19:04.680
and acted accordingly, wipe down
any surfaces we might have touched,

00:19:04.680 --> 00:19:06.940
disposed of my shoes
in a random dumpster.

00:19:06.940 --> 00:19:09.960
James wanted to throw away the
paperweight, but I couldn't bear

00:19:09.960 --> 00:19:13.020
to part with it so I took it
home and washed it lovingly,

00:19:13.020 --> 00:19:14.320
hid it underneath the bed.

00:19:14.320 --> 00:19:17.480
And then we held our
collective breath.

00:19:17.480 --> 00:19:21.150
When no one arrived to arrest us
the next day or the day after that

00:19:21.150 --> 00:19:24.490
or the week after that, we
thought we were in the clear.

00:19:24.490 --> 00:19:26.080
We thought we got away with murder.

00:19:26.080 --> 00:19:29.760
And then I came home one afternoon
to find George Harrison's dishes

00:19:29.760 --> 00:19:32.280
in the middle of the
living room floor.

00:19:32.280 --> 00:19:33.880
I swallowed the panic that
was rising in my throat

00:19:33.880 --> 00:19:38.020 position:56%
and carried the dishes into the
kitchen where, on the kitchen table,

00:19:38.020 --> 00:19:40.180
was a newspaper clipping held

00:19:40.180 --> 00:19:42.760
down by two globe-shaped
paperweights,

00:19:42.760 --> 00:19:45.310
one green and one blue.

00:19:45.310 --> 00:19:49.510
Choking on terror I peered down
at the clipping, Megan's obituary.

00:19:49.510 --> 00:19:53.040
And written across it in red marker
were the words, "Wrong answer.

00:19:53.040 --> 00:19:54.810
Better luck next time."

00:19:54.810 --> 00:19:57.510
So thank you.

