00:43:53.070 --> 00:43:54.620
Maybe -- all right.

00:43:54.620 --> 00:43:56.630
So I'm going to read
a short section.

00:43:56.630 --> 00:43:58.470
Now, you should be able to follow.

00:43:58.470 --> 00:44:00.070
Ambler is the Raymond Ambler,

00:44:00.070 --> 00:44:04.460
the Curator of the
Crime Fiction Collection

00:44:04.460 --> 00:44:08.660
at the New York Public Library,
the 42nd Street Library.

00:44:08.660 --> 00:44:12.400
What struck Ambler
was a coincidence.

00:44:12.400 --> 00:44:18.730
A week before he'd gotten a
call from an upstate prison --

00:44:18.730 --> 00:44:23.620
actually the call was from
his son who is in prison.

00:44:23.620 --> 00:44:27.130
You have to read the first book
to understand why he was there.

00:44:27.130 --> 00:44:32.140
But a lifer there told his son
he was a friend of his father

00:44:32.140 --> 00:44:34.010
and wanted to talk to him.

00:44:34.010 --> 00:44:39.050
The prisoner, Devon Thomas, in
fact had been Ambler's friend,

00:44:39.050 --> 00:44:43.050
a very good friend from 6th
grade until Devon dropped

00:44:43.050 --> 00:44:45.780
out of high school at 16 to run

00:44:45.780 --> 00:44:50.530 position:56%
with the Black Peoples' Party the
last time Ambler had seen him except

00:44:50.530 --> 00:44:53.990
in a Daily News photo
wearing handcuffs.

00:44:53.990 --> 00:44:57.530
On his monthly visit to his
son the previous Saturday,

00:44:57.530 --> 00:45:00.210
Ambler looked up his friend.

00:45:00.210 --> 00:45:04.500
Devon told him he was in prison
for a murder he didn't commit.

00:45:04.500 --> 00:45:07.920
"My kid brother did the murder."

00:45:07.920 --> 00:45:09.440
Devon told him.

00:45:09.440 --> 00:45:11.970
His hard stare faltered.

00:45:11.970 --> 00:45:14.080
"Trey was a snitch.

00:45:14.080 --> 00:45:18.510
I took the rap because I knew
someone would kill him in here."

00:45:18.510 --> 00:45:19.810
"And now?"

00:45:19.810 --> 00:45:21.160
Ambler asked?

00:45:21.160 --> 00:45:24.020
"He died a couple of weeks ago."

00:45:24.020 --> 00:45:27.270
A skeptical person might
doubt Devon's story

00:45:27.270 --> 00:45:31.870
that he'd spent his adult life in
prison for a crime he didn't commit

00:45:31.870 --> 00:45:34.670
out of loyalty to his brother.

00:45:34.670 --> 00:45:36.750
Ambler believed him.

00:45:36.750 --> 00:45:41.080
He'd met Devon in 6th grade
at a new school for Ambler.

00:45:41.080 --> 00:45:44.560
The first day he was
surrounded in the hallway

00:45:44.560 --> 00:45:49.950
by a half dozen would-be -- he
was surrounded in the hallway

00:45:49.950 --> 00:45:55.190
by a half dozen would-be hoodlums
taunting him for some imagined

00:45:55.190 --> 00:46:00.440
or fabricated slight when he
felt an arm around his shoulder.

00:46:00.440 --> 00:46:04.960
It was Devon, who amiably
brushed aside the thugs

00:46:04.960 --> 00:46:08.460
and walked him into the classroom.

00:46:08.460 --> 00:46:12.250 position:56%
Ambler knew some of the history
behind Devon's arrest and conviction

00:46:12.250 --> 00:46:16.230
because it was major news
in the tabloids at the time.

00:46:16.230 --> 00:46:19.830
In the early '80s, a group of truck
drivers took on a corrupt union

00:46:19.830 --> 00:46:22.520
in the garment trucking industry.

00:46:22.520 --> 00:46:25.610
One of the leaders of the
insurgence, Richard Wright,

00:46:25.610 --> 00:46:30.190
was murdered shortly after he was
elected president of the local

00:46:30.190 --> 00:46:32.840
in a government monitored election.

00:46:32.840 --> 00:46:35.890
"Devon Thomas killed
him," the newspapers said,

00:46:35.890 --> 00:46:40.710
"in a feud between rival
gangs over drug territory."

00:46:40.710 --> 00:46:42.940
"No way I killed him," Devon said.

00:46:42.940 --> 00:46:45.060
"I loved him like a father.

00:46:45.060 --> 00:46:46.380
Trey was a rat.

00:46:46.380 --> 00:46:48.570
A snitch. I didn't know.

00:46:48.570 --> 00:46:49.870
Never thought it.

00:46:49.870 --> 00:46:53.950
Never suspected until he
got scared and told me.

00:46:53.950 --> 00:46:57.760
Told me his handler
told him to off Richard.

00:46:57.760 --> 00:47:02.810
When he told me, I wanted
to kill Trey myself.

00:47:02.810 --> 00:47:06.250
You become a snitch because
you're paid or you do it

00:47:06.250 --> 00:47:08.840
to keep yourself out of prison.

00:47:08.840 --> 00:47:13.960
His handler from the NYPD
told Trey he'd get off.

00:47:13.960 --> 00:47:16.700
Then, something went wrong and
the handler told Trey he'd have

00:47:16.700 --> 00:47:18.950
to plead to manslaughter.

00:47:18.950 --> 00:47:21.980
They'd get him out in three years.

00:47:21.980 --> 00:47:25.400
Trey told me he wacked Richard
and was going up for it.

00:47:25.400 --> 00:47:26.950
I couldn't let him do it.

00:47:26.950 --> 00:47:28.280
I took the rap.

00:47:28.280 --> 00:47:31.310
I thought I'd get the same deal.

00:47:31.310 --> 00:47:35.750
They told Trey manslaughter,
a three year bid.

00:47:35.750 --> 00:47:38.980
Ha! I got life."

00:47:38.980 --> 00:47:42.860
Devon's hair, still
kinky, had turned gray.

00:47:42.860 --> 00:47:46.940
Tight curls now where years
ago it was a giant afro.

00:47:46.940 --> 00:47:50.800
His eyes were clear, still
hard, still something friendly

00:47:50.800 --> 00:47:55.720
in them too, a flash of
kindness behind the hard.

00:47:55.720 --> 00:47:58.930
His skin darker than
Ambler remembered,

00:47:58.930 --> 00:48:04.420
his features as much European as
African, a slender nose, thin lips.

00:48:04.420 --> 00:48:08.510
He'd developed the prison
body, muscular, athletic.

00:48:08.510 --> 00:48:11.590
As he talked he'd reach out
now and again putting his hand

00:48:11.590 --> 00:48:15.470
on Ambler's forearm to make
sure he had his attention,

00:48:15.470 --> 00:48:17.920
to reinforce the connection.

00:48:17.920 --> 00:48:20.310
He did this now.

00:48:20.310 --> 00:48:22.420
"Trey got the AIDS.

00:48:22.420 --> 00:48:26.230
I got compassion leave the
visit him in the hospice.

00:48:26.230 --> 00:48:28.210
He was out of his head a lot.

00:48:28.210 --> 00:48:32.810
Right before he died he told
me he didn't kill Richard.

00:48:32.810 --> 00:48:35.170
They killed him."

00:48:35.170 --> 00:48:37.960
"Who's 'They?'" Ambler asked?

00:48:37.960 --> 00:48:39.300
Devon shook his head.

00:48:39.300 --> 00:48:40.600
"I don't know.

00:48:40.600 --> 00:48:42.300
I got some ideas.

00:48:42.300 --> 00:48:45.160
I've been going back over
what happened back then.

00:48:45.160 --> 00:48:48.980
I'm using the prison
library, but it's slow.

00:48:48.980 --> 00:48:54.930
I thought you might see what you
can find in that library of yours

00:48:54.930 --> 00:48:57.510
about what happened back then.

00:48:57.510 --> 00:48:58.810
I read about you.

00:48:58.810 --> 00:49:00.750
That's what you do, right?

00:49:00.750 --> 00:49:05.950
You find out what really
happened when someone was killed?"

00:49:05.950 --> 00:49:08.410
"Not exactly," Ambler said.

00:49:08.410 --> 00:49:10.350
"You can tell the truth now, right?

00:49:10.350 --> 00:49:11.650
Your brother's dead.

00:49:11.650 --> 00:49:13.740
You didn't commit the murder."

00:49:13.740 --> 00:49:15.960
Devon's eyes locked on Ambler's.

00:49:15.960 --> 00:49:18.390
"Who'd believe me?"

00:49:18.390 --> 00:49:20.790
Ambler nodded.

00:49:20.790 --> 00:49:22.090
"I know you, Ray.

00:49:22.090 --> 00:49:24.160
We were bros."

00:49:24.160 --> 00:49:25.460
Devon laughed.

00:49:25.460 --> 00:49:29.680
It began as a kind of giggle
catching on like an uncertain motor

00:49:29.680 --> 00:49:34.240
until it became a chuckle
and then a full out laugh.

00:49:34.240 --> 00:49:37.790
The sound of it rolled back the
years to the endless summers he

00:49:37.790 --> 00:49:41.510
and Devon, baseball gloves
and bats over their shoulders,

00:49:41.510 --> 00:49:44.920
rambled through Flatbush
seeking out pick-up games

00:49:44.920 --> 00:49:47.650
in schoolyards and vacant lots.

00:49:47.650 --> 00:49:50.310
The nights they played stick
ball under the street lights

00:49:50.310 --> 00:49:54.590
between the parked cars on E and
19th Street off Beverley Road.

00:49:54.590 --> 00:49:56.890
OK. That's it.

00:49:56.890 --> 00:49:59.190
Thank you.

00:50:00.250 --> 00:50:04.700
I have a book to raffle off if
you think you can handle it.

00:50:04.700 --> 00:50:07.000
Eh [laughing]?

